g.text: • Everything in JavaScript happens inside the execution context.

g.text: II. Components of the Execution Context (EC)

text.font-family: Nunito, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: The EC consists of two main components:

text.font-family: Nunito, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji
Nunito, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 1. Memory Component

text.font-family: Nunito, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • Purpose: This is the place where all variables and functions are stored.

text.font-family: Nunito, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • Storage Format: Items are stored as key-value pairs (e.g., if variable A equals 10, it is stored here).

text.font-family: Nunito, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • Alternative Name: The memory component is also known as the variable environment.

g.text: 2. Code Component

g.text: • Purpose: This is the place where the code is executed.

text.font-family: Nunito, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • Execution Style: Code is executed one line at a time.

g.text: III. The Nature of JavaScript

text.font-family: Nunito, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • JavaScript is a synchronous singlethreaded language.

text.font-family: Nunito, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • Singlethreaded: This means JavaScript can execute only one command at a time.

text.font-family: Nunito, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • Synchronous Singlethreaded: This implies that JavaScript executes one command at a time and in a specific order.

g.text: Detailed Notes on JavaScript Execution

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: I. Execution Context (EC) Fundamentals

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • Everything in JavaScript happens inside an Execution Context (EC). JavaScript is not possible without this.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • When a JavaScript program runs, an Execution Context is created. For the overall program, a Global Execution Context (GEC) is created.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • The EC is described as a big box and contains two main components:

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 1. Memory Component (Variable Environment): Where variables and functions are stored.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 2. Code Component (Thread of Execution): Where the code is executed one line at a time (reflecting JavaScript's synchronous, single-threaded nature, as mentioned previously).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: II. The Two Phases of EC Creation

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: The creation of an Execution Context (whether Global or local function EC) happens in two distinct phases:

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: Phase 1: Memory Creation Phase (Allocation)

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • This is a critical phase where JavaScript allocates memory to all variables and functions.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • JavaScript skims through the whole program line by line during this phase.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • Variables:

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ◦ As soon as a variable is encountered (e.g., n, square2, square4), memory is reserved.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ◦ A special value known as undefined is allocated and stored in memory for variables. undefined acts as a placeholder.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ◦ For variables inside a function (parameters like num and local variables like ans), memory is allocated, and they are also assigned undefined.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • Functions:

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ◦ In the case of functions (e.g., square), the JavaScript Engine literally stores the whole code of the function inside the memory space allocated for that function.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: Phase 2: Code Execution Phase

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • In this phase, JavaScript runs through the whole program line by line once again and executes the code. This is when all calculations and functions are executed.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • Variables: The allocated undefined values are replaced with the actual values. For example, when n=2 is executed, the value 2 replaces undefined in the memory space for n.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: III. Function Invocation and Local ECs

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • Functions are considered the heart of JavaScript and act like a mini-program.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • When a function is invoked (called with parentheses, e.g., square(n)), a brand new Execution Context is created.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • This new EC exists inside the current execution context (e.g., inside the GEC).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • The new EC also goes through the same two phases (Memory Creation and Code Execution).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • Code Execution within a Function:

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ◦ The argument (e.g., the value of n, which is 2) is passed to the parameter (e.g., num). The value replaces the initial undefined placeholder for the parameter.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ◦ Calculations are performed, and the resulting value (e.g., 4) replaces undefined for the local variables (e.g., ans).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ◦ Return Statement: The return keyword signals the function is done with its work. It returns the control of the program and the calculated value (e.g., 4, the value of ans) back to the execution context where the function was originally invoked (e.g., line 6).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: IV. Managing Execution Contexts: The Call Stack

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • Managing the creation, deletion, and control flow of potentially many nested Execution Contexts (ECs) is difficult for the JS Engine.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • JavaScript manages this complexity using a Call Stack.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • The Call Stack is an essential feature of JavaScript that acts as a stack.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • Function: The Call Stack maintains the order of execution of Execution Contexts.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • Lifecycle Management:

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 1. When any JS program runs, the Global Execution Context (GEC) is pushed onto the bottom of the Call Stack.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 2. Whenever a new Execution Context is created (i.e., when a function is invoked), it is pushed into the stack.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 3. When an Execution Context finishes (e.g., a function executes its return statement and its EC is deleted), it is popped out of the stack. Control then returns to the EC below it.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 4. Once the entire program is executed, the GEC is popped off, and the call stack gets empty.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: • Alternative Names: The Call Stack is also known by several names, including Execution context stack, Program stack, Control stack, Runtime stack, and Machine stack.

g.text: ### 1. Hoisting in JavaScript

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Definition:** Hoisting is a phenomenon in JavaScript that allows you to access variables and functions even before they have been initialized or defined in the code, typically without throwing an error.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Mechanism:** This "magic" occurs because, even before the code starts executing, JavaScript performs a **Memory Creation Phase** (the first phase of the Execution Context creation). In this phase, memory is allocated to all variables and functions.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * Accessing the variable before its assignment prints `undefined`.

g.text: * **`not defined` (ReferenceError):** This error means the variable was not present in the memory at all. This occurs if the variable declaration (like `var x;`) is completely absent from the program, and JavaScript throws an error when trying to access it.

g.text: ### 3. Execution Context and Call Stack

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: **Execution Context (EC)**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * An execution context is created whenever JavaScript code runs.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * It is created in two phases: the **Memory Creation Phase** (where hoisting occurs) and the Code Execution Phase.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: **Call Stack**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * The Call Stack manages the flow of execution contexts.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * When the JavaScript program starts, a **Global Execution Context (GEC)** is created and pushed onto the call stack (often labeled as `anonymous`).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * When a function is invoked, a **brand new execution context** for that function is created and pushed on top of the stack.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * Once a function finishes executing, its execution context is deleted and **popped off the call stack**.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * The call stack is empty once all code finishes executing.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * *Note:* The sources describe the operation of the Call Stack through a demo using debugging tools, showing the creation, pushing, and popping of the Global EC and a function EC (`get name` EC).

g.text: **Short Notes on the JavaScript Global Environment (Based on Browser Context)**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### Global Execution and Objects

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Shortest Program:** The shortest JavaScript program can be an empty file.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Execution Context:** When a JavaScript program is run, the **Global Execution Context** is created.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Global Object Creation:** A **Global Object** is created along with the Global Execution Context. All JavaScript engines are responsible for creating this Global Object.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **The `window` Object:** In the context of browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge), the Global Object is known as the **`window` object**.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * The `window` object is a large object containing many built-in functions and variables. It acts as the global space, allowing functions and variables to be accessed anywhere in the JavaScript program.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### The `this` Keyword

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * The **`this` keyword** is created alongside the Global Object.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Global Relationship:** At the global level, the `this` keyword points to the Global Object.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * Specifically, in a browser environment, **`this` is equal to `window`**. This equality is confirmed to be true.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### Global Variables and the Window Object

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Variable Attachment:** When variables are created using `var` at the top level (outside of any function), they are automatically attached to the Global Object (`window`).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * For example, declaring `var a = 10` automatically makes `a` a property of the `window` object (`window.a = 10`). Everything created at the top level is attached to the `window` object.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Implicit Access:** JavaScript allows access to these global properties without explicitly referencing the `window` object. If you call a variable or function without putting anything in front of it (like `console.log(a)`), the JavaScript engine automatically prefixes it with `window.` internally (making it equivalent to `console.log(window.a)`).

g.text: ### 2. JavaScript Execution Context

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * When JavaScript code runs, the **Global Execution Context** is created.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * As part of this context creation, the engine performs **memory allocation** for all variables and functions **before a single line of code is executed**.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * This pre-execution memory allocation is where variables receive the initial `undefined` placeholder.

g.text: ### 3. Loose Typing (Weakly Typed Language)

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * JavaScript is known as a **loosely typed language** (or **weakly typed language**).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Flexibility:** This means that a variable is **not permanently attached to a specific data type**.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Type Changes:** A single variable can be assigned a string, then later a number, and then later a boolean, all within the same program, which is considered perfectly valid JavaScript code.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * The language handles type conversion and management automatically behind the scenes, making it highly flexible.

g.text: These notes summarise the new concepts of Scope, Lexical Environment, and the Scope Chain, which are core fundamentals of JavaScript execution, alongside relevant prior knowledge from our conversation history.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ## I. Scope and Lexical Environment (LE)

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### A. Scope Definition

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Scope** determines precisely where you can access a specific variable or function within your code.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### B. Execution Context and LE

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * A **Lexical Environment (LE)** is directly related to scope.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * An LE is created whenever an **Execution Context (EC)** is created (e.g., for the Global scope or when a function is called).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### C. Lexical Environment Structure

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * The LE of any EC consists of two main parts:

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 1. **Local Memory:** All local variables and functions declared within that execution context.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 2. **Reference to the Lexical Environment of its Parent:** A pointer to the next outer scope.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Lexical Means:** "Lexical" means in **sequence** or **hierarchy**; it is determined by where the code is **physically written** (or sitting).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * If function C is physically written inside function A, then A is the **Lexical Parent** of C.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * If function A is written in the Global space, the Global scope is the Lexical Parent of A.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ## II. The Scope Chain (Variable Lookup)

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### A. Definition

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * The **Scope Chain** is the entire hierarchy or chain of these interconnected Lexical Environments (linked by the Parent LE references).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * It is the mechanism used by the JavaScript engine to find variables or functions outside the current local memory.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### B. Variable Lookup Process

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: When the JavaScript engine tries to access a variable (e.g., `b`):

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 1. **Local Check:** It first attempts to find the variable in the **Local Memory** of the current Execution Context.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 2. **Chain Check (Parent):** If the variable is not found locally, the engine uses the **Parent LE reference** to search the Lexical Environment of the parent scope.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 3. **Chain Check (Upwards):** This search process continues up the Scope Chain (Parent $\rightarrow$ Grandparent $\rightarrow$ Global).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 4. **Chain Termination:** The chain terminates when it reaches the Global scope, which points to **`null`** (it has no parent).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 5. **Error:** If the variable is not found anywhere in the entire Scope Chain, the search stops, and the engine throws a **"Not Defined" error**.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ## III. Integrating Previous Concepts

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **`let` and `const`:** These keywords (introduced in ES6) behave very differently from `var` concerning scope and are crucial for understanding modern JavaScript scoping.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Global Execution:** The shortest JS program creates the **Global Execution Context** [Conversation History].

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Browser Global:** In a browser, the Global Object is the **`window` object** [Conversation History].

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Global `this`:** Globally, the **`this` keyword** points to the Global Object (`window`) [Conversation History].

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **`var` vs. `undefined`:** Variables are allocated memory and initialised with the value **`undefined`** during the initial execution context creation phase [Conversation History].

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: The following short notes summarize the key concepts regarding `let`, `const`, the Temporal Dead Zone (TDZ), and hoisting, drawing directly from the video transcript.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ## Short Notes: `let` & `const` in JavaScript

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### 1. Hoisting and Memory Allocation

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: While historically it was sometimes taught that `let` and `const` are not hoisted, the technically correct answer is that **`let` and `const` declarations are hoisted**. However, their behaviour differs significantly from `var`.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **`var` Hoisting:** `var` variables are hoisted and allocated memory. They are assigned a special placeholder value of `undefined` even before the code execution reaches their declaration line. They are also attached to the **Global Object** (e.g., `window` object).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **`let`/`const` Hoisting:** They are hoisted and allocated memory, but they are stored in a **separate memory space** from the Global Object. Critically, they are *not* immediately initialized or assigned any value.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### 2. The Temporal Dead Zone (TDZ)

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: The inability to access `let` and `const` before they are assigned a value is due to the **Temporal Dead Zone (TDZ)**.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Definition:** The TDZ is the time phase between when a `let` or `const` variable is hoisted (memory allocated) and when the execution reaches the line where it is initialized or assigned a value.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Effect:** If you attempt to access a variable while it is in the TDZ, the JavaScript engine throws a **ReferenceError** (e.g., "Cannot access 'A' before initialization").

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Ending the TDZ:** The variable exits the TDZ once the line of code initializing it is executed.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### 3. Key Differences and Error Types

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: | Feature | `var` | `let` | ` const` |

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: | **Hoisting/Initialization** | Hoisted; initialized with `undefined`. | Hoisted; stays in TDZ until initialization. | Hoisted; stays in TDZ until initialization. |

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: | **Global Object Attachment**| Yes (e.g., attached to `window`). | No (stored in a separate memory space). | No (stored in a separate memory space). |

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: | **Redeclaration (Same Scope)| Allowed (very lenient). | **Not allowed** (**SyntaxError**). | **Not allowed** (**SyntaxError**). |

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: | **Declaration & Assignment**| Can be separated. | Can be separated. | **Must be in the same line** (Else **SyntaxError**: "Missing initialization"). |

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: | **Reassignment After Init** | Allowed. | Allowed. | **Not allowed** (**TypeError**: "Assi gnment to constant variable"). |

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### 4. Best Practices

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: It is recommended to use `const` whenever possible for values that are not meant to change. If reassignment is needed, use `let`. Avoiding `var` helps prevent unexpected errors related to `undefined` values and ensures the benefit of the TDZ. To avoid entering the TDZ entirely, always put your declarations and initializations at the top of their respective scopes.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: These notes summarise the concepts of Blocks, Block Scope, and Shadowing in JavaScript, as discussed in the sources.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ## Short Notes on Block Scope and Shadowing

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### 1. The Block (Compound Statement)

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Definition:** A block is defined by **curly braces** `{}`.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Purpose:** A block is also known as a **compound statement**. Its primary use is to combine multiple JavaScript statements into a single group.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Context:** This grouping is essential because there are places in JavaScript (like after `if`, `for`, or `while` conditions) where the language expects only one statement. By using a block, you can execute multiple statements where only one is expected.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### 2. Block Scope

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Definition:** Block Scope refers to the variables and functions that are accessible *inside* a specific block.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **`let` and `const`:** Variables declared using `let` and `const` are **block-scoped**.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * They are hoisted and stored in a **separate memory space** specifically reserved for that block, not the global scope.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * They are *not* accessible once the execution leaves the block boundary. If you try to access a block-scoped `let` or `const` outside its block, it results in a "not defined" error.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **`var`:** Variables declared using `var` are *not* block-scoped; they are function-scoped or globally scoped.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * If a `var` variable is declared inside a block, it is still hoisted to the **Global Scope** (or the nearest function scope) and remains accessible outside the block.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### 3. Shadowing

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Definition:** Shadowing occurs when a variable declared inside a block has the **same name** as a variable declared outside the block. The inner variable "shadows" the outer variable within the scope of the block.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Shadowing with `let`/`const` (Perfect Shadowing):**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * When an outer variable (regardless of whether it's `var`, `let`, or `const`) is shadowed inside a block using `let` or `const`, a new block-scoped variable is created in the block's memory space.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * The value of the outer variable is unaffected by changes made to the inner, shadowed variable.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Shadowing with `var` (No Shadowing/Modification):**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * If an outer `var` variable is re-declared inside a block *using `var`*, it does **not** create a new, separate variable.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * Instead, it refers to and modifies the original variable stored in the Global Memory Space. This effectively changes the value of the outer variable.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### 4. Illegal Shadowing

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * You cannot shadow a variable declared with `let` by re-declaring it with `var` within the same scope boundary (e.g., inside the same block or function). This is considered "illegal shadowing".

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * However, you **can** shadow an outer `var` using an inner `let`.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### 5. Lexical Scope (Scope Chain)

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * Block scopes, like function scopes, follow the **Lexical Scope pattern**.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * Lexical scope means that scopes are chained ("lexically present")—one scope is inside another.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * If a variable is accessed inside a scope (like a block) but is not declared there, JavaScript looks up the scope chain to the **nearest surrounding scope** to find the variable.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: // This shows var does not adhere to block scope rules in this shadowing context.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: // 5. Accessing 'b' and 'c' (let/const): The modification was block-scoped

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: // and the original values are restored.

g.text: ## Short Notes on Closures

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### 1. Definition and Formation

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Definition:** A Closure is formed when a function is **bundled together with its surrounding state** (or "lexical environment").

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Lexical Environment:** This refers to the scope in which the function is physically written.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Mechanism:** Closures are created when an inner function is returned from an outer function. Even after the outer function's execution context is destroyed (removed from the call stack), the returned inner function (the closure) maintains access to the variables and scope of its outer function.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### 2. Lexical Scope and Access

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * The function remembers its **lexical scope** (the scope of its parent function).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * When the inner function is executed later (outside of its original environment), it tries to find the variables it needs. If they are not present locally, it looks up its lexical scope chain.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * The function doesn't just hold onto the *value* of the outer variable; it holds a **reference** to the variable itself. This means if the outer variable's value changes before the inner function is returned, the closure will access the updated value.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### 3. Practical Implications and Uses

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * Closures make certain advanced JavaScript concepts possible, such as:

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Currying:** Closures are essential for implementing currying in JavaScript.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Data Hiding (Module Design Pattern):** Closures allow variables to be encapsulated and privately managed within a function, mimicking private variables in other languages.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **State Maintenance:** They allow functions to remember certain data or states across multiple invocations, which is a powerful feature.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * Understanding closures is crucial, as they are a **most common and most important interview question** in JavaScript.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### **Video Notes: `setTimeout` and Closures Interview Question**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: #### **Part 1: Understanding JavaScript’s Non-Blocking Nature**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: **Concept:** How `setTimeout` works and why JavaScript is non-blocking.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Setup:** A function `x` contains a variable `var i = 1` and a `setTimeout` call attempting to log `i` after 3000 milliseconds, followed by a `console.log("namaste javascript")`.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Common Misconception:** Many developers expect JavaScript to wait 3000 milliseconds, print `i`, and *then* print "namaste javascript".

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Actual Behavior:** JavaScript does not wait for the timer to complete; it proceeds immediately. The output is: "namaste javascript", followed by the value of `i` (which is 1) after 3000 milliseconds.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Mechanism (Closure and Event Queue):**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 1. The callback function inside `setTimeout` forms a **closure**. This function remembers the **reference** to `i`.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 2. `setTimeout` takes this callback function, attaches a timer (e.g., 3000ms), and stores it somewhere.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 3. JavaScript then immediately proceeds to the next line and prints "namaste javascript".

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 4. Once the 3000ms timer expires, the function is taken and put back into the call stack to run.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### **Part 2: Interview Question: The Loop and `setTimeout` Trap**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: **INTERVIEW QUESTION:** **How do you print the values 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 in the console, such that 1 prints after 1 second, 2 prints after 2 seconds, 3 prints after 3 seconds, and so on?**.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: #### **Attempt 1: Using `var` inside a `for` loop (The Failure)**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: A common attempt involves using a `for` loop (running $i=1$ to $5$) and setting the timer delay to `i * 1000`.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: **Code Attempt (Conceptual):**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ```javascript

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: for (var i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: setTimeout(function() {

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: console.log(i);

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: console.log("namaste javascript");

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: **Observed Output (The Problem):**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: The code first prints "namaste javascript". Then, after 1 second, 2 seconds, 3 seconds, 4 seconds, and 5 seconds, it prints **6** repeatedly.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: **Explanation of Failure (The Closure Trap):**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: The problem occurs because of how closures and `var` (function scope) interact.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 1. **Reference vs. Value:** The callback function remembers the **reference** to `i`, not the *value* of `i` at that specific moment.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 2. **Non-Blocking Loop:** JavaScript does not wait for the timers. The `for` loop runs continuously and extremely quickly.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 3. **Variable Increment:** Since `i` is declared with `var`, it is globally available (or function-scoped, if wrapped in a function). By the time the loop finishes (and the timers start expiring), the value of `i` has incremented all the way up to **6** (the condition $i \leq 5$ fails when $i$ becomes 6).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 4. **Shared Memory Location:** All five callback functions, due to forming closures over the same lexical environment, are referring to the **same memory location** for the variable `i`. Since that shared memory location holds the final value of **6**, every callback prints 6.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: #### **INTERVIEW ANSWER/SOLUTION 1: Using `let` (The Easy Fix)**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: **Method:** Change `var` to **`let`** in the loop declaration.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: **Code (Conceptual):**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ```javascript

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: for (let i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: setTimeout(function() {

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: console.log(i); // Now logs 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 correctly

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: **Why it Works:**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * `let` is **block-scoped**.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * Crucially, for each iteration of the loop, `let` creates a **new copy of the variable `i`**.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * When `setTimeout` is called in each iteration, the callback function forms a closure with that specific, fresh, new copy of `i` (e.g., the first callback closes over $i=1$, the second over $i=2$, etc.).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * Since each callback refers to a different memory location holding its unique value, the correct sequence (1, 2, 3, 4, 5) is printed.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: #### **INTERVIEW ANSWER/SOLUTION 2: Using `var` + Explicit Closures (The Advanced Fix)**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: Smart interviewers may ask candidates to solve the problem using `var` exclusively, forbidding the use of `let`. Closures are required to fix this.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: **Goal:** Somehow provide a new copy of `i` for the `setTimeout` callback in every iteration.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: **Method:** Enclose the `setTimeout` within another function (a manual closure) and immediately invoke it, passing the current loop value (`i`) as an argument.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: **Code (Conceptual):**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ```javascript

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: for (var i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: // 1. Define a function ('close') that accepts the current 'i' as an argument (e.g., 'x').

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: function close(x) {

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: // 2. SetTimeout is wrapped inside the new function's scope.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: setTimeout(function() {

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: console.log(x); // Accesses the new copy 'x'

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: // 3. Immediately call the function, passing the current value of 'i'.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: close(i);

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: **Why it Works:**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * By calling the function `close(i)` inside the loop, the current value of `i` is passed as an argument.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * Every time the `close` function is executed, it creates a **new scope**. The parameter received (e.g., `x`) becomes a **new, unique variable** within that scope.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * The `setTimeout` callback function now forms a closure over this new local variable (`x`), ensuring that each stored callback holds a reference to a distinct copy of the loop counter value (1, 2, 3, 4, 5). This allows the intended output to be achieved using only `var`.

g.text: ## **Video Notes: Closures, Scope, and Garbage Collection**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### **I. Definition and Mechanism of Closures**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Definition:** A closure is a **function bundled together with its lexical environment (or references to its surrounding state)**.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Lexical Environment:** This refers to the environment where the function is physically placed in the code, including the local variables of the function and the variables of its outer (parent) functions. The closure retains access to its entire scope chain.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Persistence:** When a function is returned from an outer function, the closure ensures that the inner function maintains its reference to the lexical environment of the outer function, even after the outer function has finished executing. This stored environment remains in memory.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Scope Chain:** The scope chain determines where a function looks for variables: first in its own scope, then in its parent's scope (the outer environment), and so on, up to the global scope.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### **II. Scope and Variable Shadowing**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Block Scope (`let`):** When declaring a variable using `let`, it is **block-scoped**.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Parameter Variables:** Variables passed as function parameters are also included as part of the function's environment (scope).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Shadowing (Variable Conflict):** If a variable inside an inner function has the exact same name as a variable in the outer environment, the inner variable takes precedence and **shadows** the outer variable.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * When using `let` for both the global variable and a local variable with the same name, they are treated as two completely different, separate entities. The closure will only refer to the most locally scoped variable available if one exists, otherwise it will look up the scope chain.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### **III. Practical Application: Data Hiding and Encapsulation**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Usefulness:** Closures are considered highly useful and a "most beautiful part" of the language.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Data Hiding (Privacy):** Closures are a fundamental technique for achieving data privacy in JavaScript, similar to concepts found in object-oriented programming.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Private Variables:** A closure allows the creation of a variable (like a `counter`) that is defined in the outer function's scope but can only be accessed or modified via specific inner functions that are returned.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * Any attempt to access this private variable from outside the function scope will result in an error.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * This ensures that the data can only be modified by the controlled methods (e.g., `incrementCounter`) provided by the outer function, protecting the data's integrity.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Independent Instances:** Calling the outer function multiple times (e.g., `counter1` and `counter2`) generates completely separate and new closures. This means each returned function set has its own independent copy of the private variables (e.g., `counter1`'s value is independent of `counter2`'s value).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### **IV. Garbage Collection (GC) and Closures**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Garbage Collector (GC) Role:** The GC is a background process that reclaims memory that is no longer needed by the program, ensuring efficient memory utilization.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **GC Mechanism:** The GC tracks variables and references. If memory occupied by a variable is no longer reachable or used by the running program, the GC frees it up.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Closure and GC Conflict:** While closures are beneficial, they can sometimes prevent memory from being freed. If a closure holds a reference to a variable that is large or no longer logically necessary for the program flow, the GC cannot clear that memory because the variable is still technically being "used" by the closure.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Example of Retention:** If a function forms a closure over a large array (`a`), and that function is returned and kept active in the program, the entire array `a` and its associated memory must remain available, potentially delaying or preventing garbage collection for that memory block. It is important to avoid retaining unnecessary variables within closures, as this can negatively impact performance.

g.text: * **Definition:** A function without a name.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Definition:** A function expression where the function is given an internal name (e.g., `var b = function xyz() { ... }`).

g.text: * **Scope Gotcha:** The internal name (`xyz`) is **not** created in the outer scope (the global scope) and cannot be called from outside the expression. Attempting to call `xyz()` externally results in a `ReferenceError` ("xyz is not defined").

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 1. **Parameters:** The identifiers, labels, or local variables defined when the function is **created** (e.g., `param1`, `param2` inside the parentheses of the function definition). These are local variables within the function's scope.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 2. **Arguments:** The actual **values** that are passed into the function when it is invoked or called (e.g., `1, 2` when calling `a(1, 2)`).

g.text: * **Definition:** First Class Functions describe the **ability** of functions to be treated as **values**.

g.text: * **The Three Abilities:** Functions possess these abilities in JavaScript, which make them "first class":

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 2. They can be **passed into** other functions as arguments.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **First Class Citizens:** This term means the **exact same thing** as First Class Functions. It refers to the ability of functions to be used like values. This terminology is common in books and blogs.

g.text: ### **I. Fundamentals of Callback Functions**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **First Class Functions:** Functions are considered **First Class Citizens** in JavaScript. This means you can take a function and **pass it into another function**. This ability makes them very powerful.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Definition of Callback:** If a function (e.g., Function Y) is passed inside another function (e.g., Function X), the passed function (Y) is called the **Callback Function**.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Delegated Responsibility:** You pass the responsibility of calling the callback function (Y) to the outer function (X). The callback function will be called back "sometime later in the code".

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### **II. Callbacks and Asynchronous Operations (`setTimeout`)**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: `setTimeout` is a common example where a function is passed as a callback.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: #### **A. Mechanism of Asynchronous Execution**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * JavaScript is a **single-threaded language**, meaning code is executed one line at a time.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * When `setTimeout` is encountered, the callback function (the first parameter) is taken and stored in a **separate space**, and its timer (e.g., 5000 milliseconds) begins counting.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Non-Blocking Behavior:** JavaScript **does not wait** for the timer to expire. It immediately moves to the next lines of code.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * This mechanism—the ability to pass a function to be executed later without blocking the main thread—provides JavaScript with the power of **asynchronicity**.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * The **Call Stack** should **never be empty** (should always be utilized). Therefore, asynchronous operations are essential to prevent blocking the single thread.

g.text: ### **IV. Memory Management and Closures in Event Listeners**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Memory Retention:** The closure formed by an event listener holds onto the surrounding scope (e.g., the `count` variable). This means that the memory associated with those closed-over variables is **not free**.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Garbage Collection Concern:** The program cannot free up the memory associated with the counter and its surrounding scope because the user might click the button at any time, requiring the closure to be intact.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Performance Impact:** If thousands of event listeners are attached, all of them form closures, potentially consuming a lot of memory.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Best Practice:** It is considered good practice to **remove event listeners** when they are no longer needed to free up the extra memory held by these heavy closures.

g.text: ## **Simplified Notes on the JavaScript Event Loop and Asynchronous Code**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: The JavaScript (JS) engine executes code using a single thread via the **Call Stack**. However, to handle tasks that take a long time (like waiting for a timer or fetching data), the browser provides **superpowers** that allow JS to handle these tasks asynchronously (without stopping the main code flow).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### **I. Core Components of Execution**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 1. **Call Stack (Inside the JS Engine):**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * This is where all JS code runs, line by line, one item at a time.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * When the program starts, the **Global Execution Context** (GEC) is pushed onto the Call Stack.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * When a function is called, a new execution context is created and pushed onto the Stack. When it finishes, it is removed (popped off).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 2. **Browser Superpowers (Web APIs):**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * The browser (not the JS engine itself) provides powerful features like the **DOM** (Document Tree), **Local Storage**, network requests (**Fetch**), and **Timers** (`setTimeout`).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * The browser gives the JS engine access to these features via the **Window Object** (the Global Object).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### **II. Handling Asynchronous Tasks (`setTimeout`)**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: When the JS engine encounters a Web API function (like `setTimeout`), it handles it non-blocking:

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 1. The function (e.g., `setTimeout`) is executed on the Call Stack.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 2. The callback function and the timer delay are handed over to the appropriate **Web API** (the Timer feature in the browser).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 3. JS immediately moves on to the next line of code; **it does not wait** for the timer to finish.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: #### **Conceptual Execution Flow Example**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: The code uses the browser's timer superpower:

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ```javascript

g.text: console.log("start");

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: // Line 1: Logs "start" immediately.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: setTimeout(function() {

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: console.log("callback");

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: // Line 2: Callback function is registered in the Web API (timer starts).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: console.log("end");

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: // Line 3: Logs "end" immediately.

Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### **III. The Event Loop and the Queues**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: Once a Web API task is finished (e.g., the 5000ms timer expires, or a button is clicked), the associated callback function must be executed. It cannot go straight to the Call Stack; it must pass through a queue.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: #### **A. The Queues**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 1. **Callback Queue (or Macrotask Queue):**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * This is the standard waiting area for callbacks from `setTimeout` and DOM event listeners (like click handlers).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * When the timer expires, the callback function is placed here.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 2. **Microtask Queue:**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * This is a separate queue that holds callback functions that come from **Promises** (e.g., `.then()`) and Mutation Observer.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Crucially, the Microtask Queue has a higher priority than the Callback Queue**.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: #### **B. The Event Loop (The Monitor)**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * The **Event Loop** is a continuously running process.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * Its **only job** is to constantly monitor two things: the **Call Stack** and the **Queues**.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Execution Rule:** If the **Call Stack is empty**, the Event Loop picks a waiting function from a queue and pushes it onto the Call Stack for execution.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: #### **C. Priority and Starvation**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 1. The Event Loop checks the **Microtask Queue** first.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 2. If the Call Stack is empty, the Event Loop will empty **the entire Microtask Queue** before moving to the Callback Queue.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 3. **Starvation:** If new functions are continuously added to the Microtask Queue (e.g., chained Promises), the functions waiting in the lower-priority Callback Queue might never get a chance to run, leading to a situation called **Starvation**.

g.text: ## **Simplified Notes: JavaScript Engine Architecture**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### **I. The JavaScript Runtime Environment (The Container)**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: JavaScript code cannot run by itself; it requires a container known as the **JavaScript Runtime Environment**.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Definition:** The Runtime Environment includes everything needed to execute JavaScript code.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Location:** JS is ubiquitous and needs a runtime environment wherever it runs (browsers, servers, smartwatches).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Browser:** The browser provides one runtime environment (e.g., the `window` object, Local Storage, Web APIs like the Console API).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Node.js:** Node.js is another runtime environment, which also requires its own engine to execute the code.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **APIs:** Different runtime environments provide different **APIs** (superpowers). For instance, the browser provides Local Storage and DOM manipulation, while Node.js provides access to networking and the file system.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### **II. The JavaScript Engine (The Program)**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: The JavaScript Engine (like V8) is simply a **normal computer program** written by engineers (e.g., Google engineers). It is not some mystical entity.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: The JS Engine processes human-readable code through three major phases: **Parsing**, **Compilation**, and **Execution**.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: #### **A. Step 1: Parsing (Understanding the Code)**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 1. **Input:** The engine takes human-readable JavaScript code as input.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 2. **Tokenization & Parsing:** The code is broken down into small units (tokens), and the parser checks the syntax.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 3. **AST Generation:** The parser converts the valid code into an **Abstract Syntax Tree (AST)**. The AST is a tree-like, hierarchical representation of the code that the engine uses to understand the program's structure.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: #### **B. Step 2 & 3: Just-In-Time (JIT) Compilation and Execution**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: The modern JS engine uses a combination of an Interpreter and a Compiler, known as **Just-in-Time (JIT) Compilation**.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 1. **Interpreter:** The AST is passed to the Interpreter. The Interpreter's job is to quickly convert the high-level JavaScript code into **Byte Code** and begin execution. Historically, JS was considered purely interpreted (line-by-line execution), but this is no longer true for modern engines.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 2. **Compiler (Optimizer):** While the Interpreter is running the code, an Optimizing Compiler (like TurboFan) runs alongside it. The Compiler's job is to continually **optimize** the code as much as possible at runtime.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * The goal is to produce the fastest, most optimized code possible to improve performance.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * Optimization techniques include **Inlining** and **Copy Elision**.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### **III. Components Required for Execution**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: Code execution relies on two critical components inside the JS Engine:

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 1. **Call Stack:** This is where the code's execution contexts are managed (pushed and popped).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 2. **Memory Heap:** This is the region where variables and functions are assigned their memory.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### **IV. Garbage Collection (Memory Cleanup)**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * The engine also contains a **Garbage Collector (GC)** that works closely with the Memory Heap.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * The GC's job is to monitor memory and automatically **reclaim (free up) memory** that is no longer being used by the program (garbage).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * A widely used algorithm for garbage collection is called **Mark and Sweep**.

g.text: ## Notes on Higher-Order Functions and Functional Programming

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### 1. Higher-Order Functions (HOFs) Definition

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: A **Higher-Order Function (HOF)** is a function that performs one of two actions:

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 1. It takes another function as an argument (input).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 2. It returns a function from itself.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: **Callback Function:** The function that is passed into a Higher-Order Function is known as a **callback function**. This is possible in JavaScript because functions are considered "first-class citizens".

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### 2. Functional Programming (FP) Principles

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: The functional approach focuses on writing **modular** and **reusable** code.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **DRY Principle:** A key concept in software engineering is the **DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) principle**. The initial, non-functional approach often violates this principle by repeating similar code structures.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Optimal Code Structure:** Writing code in a functional fashion means thinking about the logic in terms of smaller, reusable components (functions). This increases **modularity** and **reusability**.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Interviews/Coding Rounds:** Interviewers expect candidates to write code in a modular style, breaking down logic into smaller functional units.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### 3. Demonstrating Code Optimization using HOFs

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: The core problem illustrated is calculating the area, circumference, and diameter for a list of radii.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: #### **A. Initial Approach (Non-Functional/Repetitive)**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: The initial approach involves writing separate functions for `calculateArea`, `calculateCircumference`, and `calculateDiameter`. These functions repeat approximately **90% of the code**, only changing the mathematical formula (the logic). The repeated steps include:

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * Creating a new array (`output`).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * Looping through the input array (radii).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * Pushing the result into the output array.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * Returning the output array.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: #### **B. Optimized Approach (Functional Programming using HOFs)**

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: To follow the DRY principle and write optimized code, the logic is broken down:

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 1. **Extract the Core Logic:** The calculation formulas (Area, Circumference, Diameter) are extracted into their own specialized functions. Each of these smaller functions has only one responsibility (e.g., the `area` function calculates only the area).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 2. **Create a Generic HOF:** A generic `calculate` function (a Higher-Order Function) is created to handle the repeated steps: creating the array, looping, pushing the output, and returning the array.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 3. **Pass Logic as a Callback:** The core logic functions (Area, Circumference, Diameter) are passed as arguments (callbacks) to the `calculate` HOF.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### 4. Relation to JavaScript's Built-in `map` Function

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: The custom `calculate` function written in the optimized approach is described as **exactly similar** to the built-in JavaScript array method `map`.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * `map` is a very common **Higher-Order Function** provided by JavaScript.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * Just like `calculate`, the `map` function:

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * Iterates over all elements in an array (`radius.map(...)`).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * Applies a logic function (callback) to each element.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * Returns a new array as the output.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ## 1. The `map` Function

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ## 2. The `filter` Function

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: The `filter` function is used to **filter** the values inside an array based on a specific logic or condition.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### Key Concepts

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * `filter` takes an array as input and finds a new array containing only the values that satisfy the applied logic.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * The callback function inside `filter` must return a **boolean** (`true` or `false`) for each element.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * If the logic returns `true`, the element is included in the output array; if it returns `false`, the element is skipped.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ## 3. The `reduce` Function

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: The `reduce` function is used when you must iterate over all elements of an array and **come up with a single value** out of them. Despite its name, it does not necessarily "reduce" the size; it aggregates the array into a singular output (e.g., a number, a sum, or an object).

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### Key Concepts

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * `reduce` is used for operations like finding the sum or finding the maximum number in an array.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * **Syntax:** `array.reduce(callbackFunction, initialValue)`.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * The callback function takes two main parameters:

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 1. **Accumulator (ACC):** Holds the result accumulated so far. It acts like the initialization variable (e.g., `sum` or `max`) in a traditional loop.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 2. **Current Value (CUR):** Represents the element of the array currently being processed.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: * The **`initialValue`** (second argument to `reduce`) sets the starting value of the Accumulator.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ### C. Chaining Filter and Map

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: It is possible to **chain** HOF methods like `filter` and `map`.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: Goal: Find the *first name* of all people whose age is less than 30.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 1. First, `filter` the array to keep only objects where `age < 30`.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 2. Second, `map` the resulting filtered array to extract only the `firstName` property.

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: ```javascript

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: const output = users

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: .filter((x) => x.age < 30) // Filters to objects with age 26

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: .map((x) => x.firstName); // Maps the resulting objects to their first names

text.font-family: Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: // output: ["Akshay", "Deepika"]

Comic Shanns, monospace, Segoe UI Emoji
